  "opinion": "As a woman in her eighties who's spent most of her life working with hands and minds in the electrical trade, I've learned that truth is like a circuit—sometimes it's clear, sometimes it's messy, and sometimes it's easy to get confused. Social media has become a place where I see things that don't quite add up, especially when I'm scrolling through my news feed for a little while each day. I used to be very careful with what I read and saw, but these days, with the world changing so fast, it's hard to know what's real. My faith in God helps me stay grounded, but I also know that people can be hurt by false information. I've found that the best way to handle this is to take a moment to think before I share something. If I'm not sure if a post is true, I ask myself: 'Does this align with what I know to be true?' or 'Would my church community approve of this?' Sometimes, I even call my daughter, who's a teacher, and ask her to help me check things. It's important to remember that sharing false information can cause real harm, and that's something I don't want to do. I've also learned that it's okay to say no to things that don't feel right. My time on social media is limited, but I try to use it wisely, focusing on positive connections and not getting caught up in the noise. Ultimately, it's about being thoughtful and kind, just like the way I've always treated my family and my work.",
